These modules are the original work of the zig-libs authors, consolidated
here as the canonical home. The authors' other projects depend on zig-libs,
not the reverse. A module's internal development origin — which of the
authors' own projects it was first prototyped in — is NOT recorded here: it
carries no attribution weight and would read backwards once those projects
import zig-libs. This file records only genuine THIRD-PARTY obligations and
design references — software derived from, or designed with reference to, the
third parties listed below. All are permissive (MIT/BSD-family) and
MIT-compatible. Where actual third-party code was ported (not merely
modeled), the required attribution is reproduced.

====================================================================
0. POLICY — what requires an entry here
====================================================================

A public specification or RFC is not itself a copyrightable work (merger
doctrine: a protocol/format it describes has essentially one correct
expression, and facts/ideas are not protected) — implementing one, however
closely, is not "derived from" anyone's code. Accordingly:

  - A module that is pure clean-room-from-a-public-spec/RFC, with NO
    third-party source code ported and NO third-party implementation
    studied as a design reference, needs NO entry in this file. Its
    RFC/spec citation lives in the module's own SPEC.md ("Verification" /
    design section) instead — see e.g. whois (RFC 3912), rdap (RFC
    7480-family), tar (POSIX ustar + documented GNU extensions).
  - This file is reserved for two things: (1) REQUIRED ATTRIBUTION —
    third-party source actually ported/translated, license terms
    reproduced below; (2) DESIGN REFERENCES — a named third-party
    implementation that was consulted/studied for behavior, algorithm
    shape, or API design, even when no source was copied (recorded for
    provenance so any future line-level reuse is caught).
  - Exercising an installed third-party binary purely as a black-box
    compatibility test oracle (e.g. running `tar`/`nft` and diffing
    output against this module's own encoder/decoder) is neither of the
    above and needs no entry — no source or design was consulted, only
    the program's observable behavior against its own documented format.

