2. DESIGN REFERENCES — clean-room (recorded for provenance)
====================================================================

The following modules are the authors' own original work, reimplemented from
public specifications (RFCs) or designed with reference to the named
third-party implementations below. No third-party source was copied. Each is
listed with its upstream license so any future line-level reuse is attributed
correctly. A full provenance/license audit was completed 2026-07-09; see
docs/pre-public-review.md.

  netaddr    — RFC 6724, RFC 5952 (specs); cross-checked vs Go net/addrselect
               (BSD-3-Clause, The Go Authors) + glibc getaddrinfo algorithm.
               The CIDR/prefix operations (Prefix, summarize, mergePrefixes)
               model after Go net/netip.Prefix (BSD-3-Clause) and go4.org/
               netipx (BSD-3-Clause) — behavior only, clean-room, no source
               consulted or copied.
  http       — RFC 7230/9110 (HTTP/1.1) + RFC 7541 (HPACK header compression,
               static/Huffman tables and Appendix C vectors are the RFC's own
               data) + RFC 9113 (HTTP/2 framing + stream state machine + flow
               control; RFC 7540 consulted only where it clarifies the same
               rules) + RFC 7301 (ALPN — consumed for h2-over-TLS dispatch, not
               implemented); the HTTP/2 DoS mitigations are clean-room from the
               public CVE-2023-44487 / CVE-2024-27316 advisories (behavior
               only). Conditional requests (ETag/If-* -> 304/412) are
               clean-room from RFC 9110 sec 8.8/13; the HTTP-date parser
               follows RFC 9110 sec 5.6.7 (all three formats) with the
               days-from-civil epoch conversion (Howard Hinnant's public
               algorithm). Request-body parsing is clean-room from RFC 9110
               sec 5.6.6 (Content-Type media type + parameters), the WHATWG URL
               application/x-www-form-urlencoded rules, and RFC 7578 / RFC 2046
               sec 5.1 (multipart/form-data). The Range request-header parser
               is clean-room from RFC 7233 sec 2.1 (byte-range-set); the 206
               resolution + Content-Range emitter follows RFC 7233 sec 4. The
               content-negotiation parsers are clean-room from RFC 9110
               sec 12.5.1 (Accept media-range) + sec 12.4.2 (qvalue) +
               sec 12.5.3 (Accept-Encoding) and RFC 4647 sec 3.3.1
               (Accept-Language basic filtering). Clean-room
               from the RFCs, no HPACK/HTTP-2/nghttp2 source consulted or
               copied; TLS via Zig std.crypto.tls. Design refs (behavior only,
               no source copied): lalinsky/dusty (MIT; the 1.1 client shape)
               and Go net/http (BSD-3-Clause; redirect semantics, server shape,
               gzip handler).
  dns        — RFC 1035 (wire), RFC 8484 (DoH), RFC 2782 (SRV), RFC 8659
               (CAA); design ref: miekg/dns (BSD-3-Clause) + c-ares (MIT) —
               behavior only, no source copied.
  router     — design ref: go-chi/chi (MIT), julienschmidt/httprouter
               (BSD-3-Clause).
  ratelimit  — design ref: golang.org/x/time/rate (BSD-3-Clause, The Go
               Authors), nginx limit_req.
  abuseguard — design ref: nginx limit_conn (BSD-2-Clause), fail2ban
               (GPL-2.0 — documented behavior only, no code consulted or
               copied).
  throttle   — design ref: golang.org/x/sync/semaphore (BSD-3-Clause, The Go
               Authors; slot semantics only), Netflix concurrency-limits
               (Apache-2.0; design notes only), SEDA (Welsh et al., SOSP '01
               paper — bounded-queue load shedding).
  security-headers — design ref: helmet.js (MIT; defaults vocabulary + the
               `csp_helmet_default` constant reproducing helmet's default
               policy VALUE as configuration data, no source copied), OWASP
               Secure Headers Project; header semantics from RFC 6797 (HSTS),
               CSP Level 3, Fetch/HTML specs (COOP/CORP/COEP), RFC 9110.
  cors       — design ref: rs/cors (Go, MIT; preflight interception + the
               origin/method/header gate semantics) and expressjs/cors (MIT;
